comment.editorialComment: There have been a few years recently where values have increased during September and although that sounds positive, it hasn’t become the normal pattern. Things are always expected to be a bit more buoyant at this time of the year because of the extra activity around the new plate which inevitably drives some fresh used car stock into the market. However, trade buyers will tend to exercise some caution when assessing product in this sector because just around the corner are the tougher months and they won’t want to be exposed to ageing stock unless it stands in at the right value. This means that bids are usually quite cautious and the effect of that is some pressure on used values.

It’s usual to see some sort of downward movement as we go through October and buyers start to think about the approaching year end and particularly about how much their stock is likely to depreciate during the quieter months ahead. Luckily, volumes in this sector are fairly stable and providing that there is still a reasonable amount of confidence in the market then it should be business as usual. That doesn’t make this sector immune from pressure on values and it would be normal to see an overall movement of somewhere between -0.5% to -1.0% during the course of the month.

November is the time of the year when we expect to see a general slowdown in activity levels which affects both trade and retail buyers alike. Showroom traffic will decrease and on the back of that wholesale buyer activity will usually decrease. Trade buyers are particularly cautious at this time of the year, particularly if they are bound by tight stock control regimes and have to think very carefully about what they buy, how much they pay and of course, how long they are likely to be holding that stock. With this in mind, buyers bid cautiously and vendors who need to keep the stock moving will end up taking the lower offers. Overall movement in this sector is usually somewhere around -1.5% to -2.0% during the course of the month.
